@Node SCDPLyrics "SCDPLyrics 1.0"
SCDPLyrics is an ARexx script for @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} that allows synchronized lyrics in a separate window. For this, the script uses MUIRexx by Russel Leighton.

SCDPLyrics has been inspired by RexxCD (by Urban Lindeskog, also in Aminet) Lyrics capabilities.

For SCDPLyrics to run properly, MUIRexx executable should be in MUIRexx: assign directory. Also the supplied command "Delay" should be copied somewhere in the default path, or made resident.

Two @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} scripts for controlling SCDPLyrics are supplied:

    - StartLyrics.scdp: Runs SCDPLyrics and opens its window.
	
    - QuitLyrics.scdp: Stops SCDPLyrics, closing its window.
	
If you want to use SCDPLyrics, @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} should be configured to run QuitLyrics.scdp when it quits. It may be done adding the ToolType:

    SCRIPTONQUIT=Rexx/QuitLyrics.scdp
	
For starting it whenever you start @{b}SCDPlayer,@{ub} add this ToolType:

    SCRIPTONSTART=Rexx/StartLyrics.scdp
	
If you want to start it manually, you may execute StartLyrics.scdp using the "Execute..." item in @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} ARexx menu, or installing the script in the menu using:

    MENUSCRIPT=Rexx/StartLyrics.scdp
	
Also you could start it using a RexxButton.

For SCDPLyrics showing correctly the lyrics, these must be put in a file, in the correct format (which I borrowed from RexxCD). First, the file name should be the same of ID-file for the CD for which you want to enter the lyrics, but changing 'ID' for 'LY'.

In this file, for each track which has lyrics, you should enter:

#n
mm:ss.t Lyric_line1
mm:ss.t Lyric_line2

Where 'n' is the number of the track, mm:ss.t the time of the track (minutes:seconds.tenths of second) at which you want to appear the lyrics you have typed next.

Note that '.t.' is optional (if it doesn't appear, it will be taken as '.0') and that there shouldn't be any blank line in the lyrics for a track. You should repeat this format for each track with lyrics.

This format is roughly compatible to that of RexxCD, except for the fact that RexxCD stores lyrics information in the ID-file, rather than in a separate one, as SCDPLyrics does. If you want to use some lyrics supplied for RexxCD, the only thing you have to do is to rename the ID-file, changing 'ID' for 'LY' (and removing ID information if you aren't too lazy).

@{u}NEW:@{uu} Since version 1.7 @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} includes an optional RexxButton (uncomment the tooltype) for helping make lyrics files. It's name is "Record.scdp" and when the button is pressed the time for actual track is appended to the file "RAM:SCDPLT". You can use this file afterwards for making the lyrics file.
@EndNode

@Node ARexx "SCDPlayer 1.7 ARexx port"
Since version 1.5 @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} has an ARexx port. It has a lot of commands for controlling the CD drive and the CD database.

@{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} can launch ARexx scripts. It has a menu for launching them, and buttons (RexxButtons) may be configured to launch scripts also. Besides @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} can be configured to launch some scripts when the program starts, when it quits, or when a CD is inserted.

One important thing about @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} ARexx scripts is that @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} won't quit until all scripts it has launched have finished. This means that if an ARexx script remains in a loop without exiting @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} will never quit.

For avoiding this, all scripts which don't exit immediately should use the function @{" USERACTION " Link USERACTION} for quitting when @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} wants to quit and perhaps when user press some buttons.

@{b}List of ARexx commands:@{ub}

    @{" PLAYRAW " Link PLAYRAW}              @{" SAVEPROGRAM " Link SAVEPROGRAM}   @{" FASTFORWARD " Link FASTFORWARD}
    @{" PLAYTRACK " Link PLAYTRACK}            @{" CDTITLE " Link CDTITLE}       @{" EJECT " Link EJECT}
    @{" PLAYINGPOS " Link PLAYINGPOS}           @{" CDARTIST " Link CDARTIST}      @{" LOAD " Link LOAD}
    @{" PLAYINGTRACK " Link PLAYINGTRACK}         @{" TRACKS " Link TRACKS}        @{" VOLUME " Link VOLUME}
    @{" PROGRAM " Link PROGRAM}              @{" TRACKNAME " Link TRACKNAME}     @{" IDFILENAME " Link IDFILENAME}
    @{" SHUFFLE " Link SHUFFLE}              @{" TRACKSTART " Link TRACKSTART}    @{" DISKSPATH " Link DISKSPATH}
    @{" REPEAT " Link REPEAT}               @{" TRACKEND " Link TRACKEND}      @{" OPENLIST " Link OPENLIST}
    @{" AUTOPROGRAM " Link AUTOPROGRAM}          @{" ISDATATRACK " Link ISDATATRACK}   @{" CLOSELIST " Link CLOSELIST}
    @{" AUTOSHUFFLE " Link AUTOSHUFFLE}          @{" SAVECDDATA " Link SAVECDDATA}    @{" OPENPROGRAM " Link OPENPROGRAM}
    @{" AUTOREPEAT " Link AUTOREPEAT}           @{" PLAY " Link PLAY}          @{" CLOSEPROGRAM " Link CLOSEPROGRAM}
    @{" AUTOPLAY " Link AUTOPLAY}             @{" STOP " Link STOP}          @{" STATUS " Link STATUS}
    @{" SETPROGRAM " Link SETPROGRAM}           @{" PAUSE " Link PAUSE}         @{" USERACTION " Link USERACTION}
    @{" PROGRAMMEDTRACKS " Link PROGRAMMEDTRACKS}     @{" PREVIOUS " Link PREVIOUS}      @{" SLEEP " Link SLEEP}
    @{" PROGRAMMEDTRACK " Link PROGRAMMEDTRACK}      @{" NEXT " Link NEXT}
    @{" ADDPROGRAMMEDTRACK " Link ADDPROGRAMMEDTRACK}   @{" REWIND " Link REWIND}
    
All these commands return a return code of 0 if all went ok, or 5 if an error occurred. Also, if the result string is supposed to be a number, it will be -1 if an error occurred.
@EndNode

@Node PLAYRAW
@{b}PLAYRAW STARTADDRESS/N/A,ENDADDRESS/N@{ub}

This command will play the CD from the start address given to the end address, if given, or the end of the CD otherwise. It will fail if no disc is inserted.

The addresses are in index units. There are 75 index units in a second.
@EndNode

@Node PLAYTRACK
@{b}PLAYTRACK TRACK/N/A@{ub}

This command will play the specified track. It will fail if no disc is inserted or the track number is wrong.
@EndNode

@Node PLAYINGPOS
@{b}PLAYINGPOS@{ub}

This command will return the CD position being played in index units. It will fail if no disc is inserted or it is not playing or paused.

The addresses are in index units. There are 75 index units in a second.
@EndNode

@Node PLAYINGTRACK
@{b}PLAYINGTRACK@{ub}

This command will return the CD track being played. It will fail if no disc is inserted or it is not playing or paused.
@EndNode

@Node PROGRAM
@{b}PROGRAM NEW/N@{ub}

This command will return the status of Program mode button. It will return 1 if the button is selected (and Program Mode active) or 0 otherwise.

You also may specify a new value in NEW for enabling/disabling Program Mode.
@EndNode

@Node SHUFFLE
@{b}SHUFFLE NEW/N@{ub}

This command will return the status of Shuffle mode button. It will return 1 if the button is selected (and Shuffle Mode active) or 0 otherwise.

You also may specify a new value in NEW for enabling/disabling Shuffle Mode.
@EndNode

@Node REPEAT
@{b}REPEAT NEW/N@{ub}

This command will return the status of Repeat mode button. It will return 1 if the button is selected (and Repeat Mode active) or 0 otherwise.

You also may specify a new value in NEW for enabling/disabling Repeat Mode.
@EndNode

@Node AUTOPROGRAM
@{b}AUTOPROGRAM NEW/N@{ub}

This command will return the status of AutoProgram mode checkmark. It will return 1 if the gadget is checked (and AutoProgram active) or 0 otherwise.

You also may specify a new value in NEW for enabling/disabling AutoProgram.
@EndNode

@Node AUTOSHUFFLE
@{b}AUTOSHUFFLE NEW/N@{ub}

This command will return the status of AutoShuffle mode checkmark. It will return 1 if the gadget is checked (and AutoShuffle active) or 0 otherwise.

You also may specify a new value in NEW for enabling/disabling AutoShuffle.
@EndNode

@Node AUTOREPEAT
@{b}AUTOREPEAT NEW/N@{ub}

This command will return the status of AutoRepeat mode checkmark. It will return 1 if the gadget is checked (and AutoRepeat active) or 0 otherwise.

You also may specify a new value in NEW for enabling/disabling AutoRepeat.
@EndNode

@Node AUTOPLAY
@{b}AUTOPLAY NEW/N@{ub}

This command will return the status of AutoPlay mode checkmark. It will return 1 if the gadget is checked (and AutoPlay active) or 0 otherwise.

You also may specify a new value in NEW for enabling/disabling AutoPlay.
@EndNode

@Node SETPROGRAM
@{b}SETPROGRAM TRACKNUMNBERS/N/M@{ub}

This command sets the programmed tracks. You supply a list of numbers, being these the track numbers of the programmed tracks. Your list is copied to the program. An empty list will get you an empty program.

It fails if a number is wrong or there is no CD inserted.
@EndNode

@Node PROGRAMMEDTRACKS
@{b}PROGRAMMEDTRACKS@{ub}

This command returns the number of tracks in the program.
@EndNode

@Node PROGRAMMEDTRACK
@{b}PROGRAMMEDTRACK NUMBER/N,NEW/N@{ub}

If no arguments are given it returns the index in the program of the track being played (fails if not in Program mode and playing).

If the first argument is given, it returns the number of the track programmed in the program index given (fails if the number is wrong).

If the second argument is given, it changes the track in program index NUMBER with that in NEW.
@EndNode

@Node ADDPROGRAMMEDTRACK
@{b}ADDPROGRAMMEDTRACK NEW/N/A@{ub}

Adds the track given in NEW at the end of the program, failing if the number is wrong.
@EndNode

@Node SAVEPROGRAM
@{b}SAVEPROGRAM@{ub}

This command saves the current program as the default program for the inserted CD.
@EndNode

@Node CDTITLE
@{b}CDTITLE TITLE@{ub}

Returns the title of the inserted CD. Fails if no CD inserted.

If the argument is given, the title is set to that.
@EndNode

@Node CDARTIST
@{b}CDARTIST ARTIST@{ub}

Returns the artist name of the inserted CD. Fails if no CD inserted.

If the argument is given, the artist is set to that.
@EndNode

@Node TRACKS
@{b}TRACKS@{ub}

Returns the total number of tracks of the inserted CD. Fails if no CD inserted.
@EndNode

@Node TRACKNAME
@{b}TRACKNAME NUMBER/N/A,NAME@{ub}

If only the first argument is given, it returns the name of the track with the number given.

If the second argument is given, it changes the track name with that in NAME.
@EndNode

@Node TRACKSTART
@{b}TRACKSTART NUMBER/N/A@{ub}

It returns the start address of the track with the number given.

The address is in index units (75 per second).
@EndNode

@Node TRACKEND
@{b}TRACKEND NUMBER/N/A@{ub}

It returns the end address of the track with the number given.

The address is in index units (75 per second).
@EndNode

@Node ISDATATRACK
@{b}ISDATATRACKSTART NUMBER/N/A@{ub}

Returns 1 if the given track is a data track or 0 otherwise.
@EndNode

@Node SAVECDDATA
@{b}SAVECDDATA@{ub}

This command saves the current track names, title and artist as the defaults for the inserted CD.
@EndNode

@Node PLAY
@{b}PLAY@{ub}

It does the same as pressing the play button in @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} main window.
@EndNode

@Node STOP
@{b}STOP@{ub}

It does the same as pressing the stop button in @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} main window.
@EndNode

@Node PAUSE
@{b}PAUSE@{ub}

It does the same as pressing the pause button in @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} main window.
@EndNode

@Node PREVIOUS
@{b}PREVIOUS@{ub}

It does the same as pressing the previous button in @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} main window.
@EndNode

@Node NEXT
@{b}NEXT@{ub}

It does the same as pressing the next button in @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} main window.
@EndNode

@Node REWIND
@{b}REWIND@{ub}

It does the same as pressing the rewind button in @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} main window.
@EndNode

@Node FASTFORWARD
@{b}FASTFORWARD@{ub}

It does the same as pressing the fastforward button in @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} main window.
@EndNode

@Node EJECT
@{b}EJECT@{ub}

It ejects the inserted CD.
@EndNode

@Node LOAD
@{b}LOAD@{ub}

It loads the tray.
@EndNode

@Node VOLUME
@{b}VOLUME LEVEL/N@{ub}

It returns the current volume level (0..255). If the LEVEL argument is given, the volume is set to that.

Note that the limits of this setting have changed since v1.7.
@EndNode

@Node IDFILENAME
@{b}IDFILENAME@{ub}

It returns the filename for the "ID-file" of the inserted CD. Fails if no CD inserted.

The "ID-file" contains the current CD info, in the following format:

    ·One line with artist's name.
    
    ·One line with CD title.
    
    ·One line for each track, with the names of the tracks.
    
    ·With newer versions (1.4 and up) a line which starts with an asterisk and has an extra character as flags for automatic functions.
    
These "ID-files" are stored in the path given with DISKSPATH Tooltype.
@EndNode

@Node DISKSPATH
@{b}DISKSPATH@{ub}

It returns the path for "ID-files" configured in DISKSPATH Tooltype.
@EndNode

@Node OPENLIST
@{b}OPENLIST@{ub}

It opens the List Window.
@EndNode

@Node CLOSELIST
@{b}CLOSELIST@{ub}

It closes the List Window.
@EndNode

@Node OPENPROGRAM
@{b}OPENPROGRAM@{ub}

It opens the Program Window.
@EndNode

@Node CLOSEPROGRAM
@{b}CLOSEPROGRAM@{ub}

It closes the Program Window.
@EndNode

@Node STATUS
@{b}STATUS@{ub}

It returns one of the following strings depending on the CD status:

    NODISK

    PLAYING
    
    STOPPED
    
    PAUSED
@EndNode

@Node USERACTION
@{b}USERACTION@{ub}

It returns one of these values:

    0 -> The user didn't do anything with @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} since the last ARexx command.
    
    1 -> The user gave some commands since the last ARexx command.
    
    2 -> @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} is trying to quit.
    
Any ARexx script that keeps waiting should call USERACTION periodicly, and quit if the result is 2 and most times also if the result is 1.
@EndNode

@Node SLEEP
@{b}SLEEP NEW/N/A@{ub}

If you give argument 1, @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} windows are marked as busy so that no user input will be processed (busy pointer).

If you give 0, They will be unfreezed.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} These commands are nested. There should be a call with 0 for each previous call with 1.
@EndNode

