        Eduard-Spranger-Straße 7
        80935 München
        GERMANY
@EndNode

@Node Bugs "Hidden features!"
I hope @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} has not any serious bug. I have found none until now.

However, the volume control of @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} is not safe. The original function in @{b}MCDPlayer@{ub} didn't work in my system, and I modified it by a process of trial-and-error until it worked. So it works on my system, but I don't know why it works, nor if it will work on any other system. If it doesn't work on yours, see NOVOLUME in @{" ToolTypes " Link ToolTypes} section.

If you know how to set properly the volume on a SCSI CD-ROM, please contact me.
@EndNode

@Node Installation "How to get it running"
Since version 1.5, @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} comes with an installation script. Simply double-click "Install" icon and answer the questions the installer will make.

@{b}NOTE 1:@{ub} The supplied installation scripts need Installer V42.9 or newer. You can get V43.3 in Aminet (I don't remember which directory).

@{b}NOTE 2:@{ub} If you select NOVICE or AVERAGE level in the installer, the icons installed will be those of NewIcons style, and the images will be the standard black ones. If you prefer MagicWB icons or 3D images, select EXPERT, and you will be given the possibility to choose.

For manual installation,simply drag @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} drawer to where you want to have it in, and set the DEVICE and UNIT @{" ToolTypes " Link ToolTypes} to tell it how to find your CD-ROM.

Check also the "alternative" drawer for alternative images and icons.
@EndNode

@Node ToolTypes "SCDPlayer's icon ToolTypes"
The following tooltypes are available in @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} icon:

@{u}DEVICE@{uu}:
Selects the exec.library device that controls the CD-ROM. The default is:

        DEVICE=scsi.device

@{u}UNIT@{uu}:
Selects the device unit in which the CD-ROM resides. The default is:

        UNIT=4

@{u}NOVOLUME@{uu}:
Setting this ToolType disables @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} volume control functionality. See @{" Bugs " Link Bugs} section.

@{u}MINVOLUME@{uu}:
Use this if your CD drive stops or does strange things when the volume is set to small values (set it to 3, for example). See @{" Bugs " Link Bugs} section. The default value is:

        MINVOLUME=0

@{u}DISKSPATH@{uu}:
This Tooltype tells @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} where to find disks and programs data. The default value for this ToolType is "PROGDIR:disks".

@{u}CUSTOMFONTS@{uu}:
Setting this ToolType makes @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} use the fonts stated in the tooltypes in place of @{b}MUI@{ub} defined fonts.

@{u}NORMALFONT | TINYFONT | FIXEDFONT | LISTFONT | TITLEFONT@{uu}: These ToolTypes set which fonts will be used for letters and buttons | titles above numbers in the display | the numbers in the display | the entries of the lists | the titles if CUSTOMFONTS is set. They must be in the format "****FONT=name/size" (the name without ".font"). As an example:

        NORMALFONT=topaz/11

@{u}CX_POPUP@{uu}:
If specified, will instruct @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} to start in iconified state, if the tooltype value is "NO" or with its window open if the value is "YES". If this tooltype is not specified, the default action is taken from MUI system preferences for @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub}.

@{u}CX_POPKEY@{uu}:
Sets the hotkey used to iconify/deiconify @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub}. The default value is "control lcommand numericpad enter".

@{u}PLAY_KEY | PAUSE_KEY | STOP_KEY | PREVIOUS_KEY | NEXT_KEY | REWIND_KEY | FASTFORWARD_KEY | EJECT_KEY | PROGRAM_KEY | SHUFFLE_KEY | REPEAT_KEY@{uu}:
These are the hotkey equivalents to the image buttons on @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} main window. They will work even when @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} is iconified. To see default values refer to @{" Usage " Link Usage} section.

@{u}SCRIPTONSTART@{uu}:
Specifies the path and name of an ARexx script that will be executed when @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} is started. The default extension is ".scdp".

@{u}SCRIPTONQUIT@{uu}:
Specifies the path and name of an ARexx script that will be executed when @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} is quitted. The default extension is ".scdp".

@{u}SCRIPTONINSERT@{uu}:
Specifies the path and name of an ARexx script that will be executed when a CD is inserte. The default extension is ".scdp".

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} The last three Tooltypes may specify ONLY ONE script. This means that if you specify, for example, two times SCRIPTONINSERT with different values only the last one will have effect.

@{u}MENUSCRIPT@{uu}:
Specifies the path and name of an ARexx script that will be shown in @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} ARexx menu, and executed if selected. The default extension is ".scdp". There can be a maximum of 8 menu scripts.

@{u}BUTTONSCRIPT@{uu}:
This Tooltype specifies the script path and name and the image for a RexxButton, one of @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} outstanding features. There can be a maximum of 8 RexxButtons. The format of these Tooltypes is "BUTTONSCRIPT=ScriptPathAndName|ImageFileName". The ARexx script has the same default extension as before. The ImageFileName should be the name of a MUIBrush located on the Images drawer in @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} drawer. For each of these Tooltypes a new button will appear in @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} main window, with the specified image, that will launch the specified ARexx script when selected.

These ToolTypes are @{b}case sensitive.@{ub} If you want to run @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} from the CLI, you'll have to type the ToolTypes you need as arguments:

        SCDP "DEVICE=scsi.device" "UNIT=4"
@EndNode

@Node Usage "How to use SCDPlayer 1.7"
You may start @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} from Workbench, double-clicking its icon, or from shell. If you start @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} from the shell, you'll have to give it arguments to set the device and unit of your CD-ROM drive (see @{" ToolTypes " Link ToolTypes}).

@{b}Note that SCDPlayer needs at least 20000 bytes of stack. You should make sure that the icon or the shell has enough stack.@{ub}

Once loaded, @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} will open its window. You'll see the @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} logo, a box showing data on current CD, a set of buttons to control the CD, a list of the titles of the songs, and two buttons more.

The information box shows what track is being played, the time played of this track and of this CD, the name of the artist and the CD, and the name of the track or CD.

The first line of buttons contains:

    @{u}Button@{uu}  @{u}Meaning@{uu}      @{u}Default keyboard shortcut@{uu}
    |>      Play         control lcommand Space
    ||      Pause        control lcommand z
    []      Stop         control lcommand x
    |<      Previous     control lcommand <
    >|      Next         control lcommand >
    <<      Rewind       control lcommand c
    >>      Fast forward control lcommand v
    @{u}^@{uu}       Eject        control lcommand `

A middle line of buttons will appear if at least one RexxButton is configured. These are buttons that the user may add (see @{" ToolTypes " Link ToolTypes}). They launch configured ARexx scripts. The configuration that comes in the archive has two buttons, one for repeating a single track and other for repeating a part of the CD.

The last line of buttons contains:

    @{u}Button@{uu}  @{u}Meaning@{uu}        @{u}Default keyboard shortcut@{uu}
    Slider  Volume control
    =       Program mode   control lcommand p
    %       Shuffle mode   control lcommand s
    @       Repeat mode    control lcommand r

These keyboard shorcuts are only the default settings. They may be changed using @{" ToolTypes " Link ToolTypes}. These hotkeys remain usable even when @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} is in iconified state.

Also, since v1.7, you may start playing a track by typing a track number while @{b}SCDPlayer's@{ub} window is active.

The list has the track titles or the programmed tracks, selectable by the register controls. The track being played appears active. If you double-click on an entry, this track gets played (program mode gets either activated or deactivated depending on the list you clicked).

The "List" button opens a window which lets you edit this information about the current CD:

    ·Artist.

    ·Title.

    ·Track titles.

There are four checkmarks for selecting how will act @{b}SCDPlayer@{ub} when a CD is inserted (Auto Play, Auto Program, Auto Shuffle & Auto Repeat).

This window has three buttons for using the edited names, saving them for further times, or cancelling the changes.

The "Program" button opens the program editing window. You get a list of playable titles, a list of the current program, a set of buttons for arrange it, and three buttons for using, saving, or cancelling the changes made to the program. You may also arrange the program by drag&drop.
@EndNode

@Node History "Program releases"
@{u}Date@{uu}    @{u}Version@{uu} @{u}Changes@{uu}
17-3-96 1.0     First release.
18-3-96 1.1     Custom font support added.
31-3-96 1.2     Fixed problem with logo on custom backgrounds.
                Changed to MUI 3.1.
                Included help bubbles.
                Made program menu drag&drop.
                Auto disappearing objects.
22-6-96 1.3     AutoPlay, AutoProgram, AutoShuffle & AutoRepeat on inserting the CD.
19-7-96 1.4     Added balancing to main window and DISKSPATH tooltype.
                Added complete commodities support, with configurable hotkeys.
                Slightly changed CD info display to show CD title everytime.
                Changed fastforward and rewind jumps to 5 seconds (were 10).
16-8-96 1.5     Added program list and tracks/program register to main window.
                Fixed some undesirable behaviours.
                Added ARexx port and example scripts.
                Fixed DISKSPATH (the Tooltype wasn't being read).
                Added installation script.
03-9-96 1.6     Now DISKSPATH ARexx command expands the path.
                Added French catalog.
                Added SCDPLyrics V1.0.
                Modified installation script.
24-9-96 1.7     Added "All" button to Program Window.
                Added help bubbles to RexxButtons (not of any help, though :).
                Changed volume to finer precision and added MINVOLUME tooltype.
                Added a RexxButton for helping with lyrics.
                Added capability to start a track by typing it's number.
                Volume slider now dissappears when disabled by NOVOLUME.
@EndNode

@Node Future "Future features"
Well, I think the program is mostly finished. The only feature I would include is, perhaps, a database file for including the info of all CD's.

(Note that the main reason for including ARexx support was for not having to implement all the suggestions I got, because now you may program them via ARexx ;-)
@EndNode

